article.headline: Houston wins third straight
article.linkText: Johnson propels Comets to OT win at San Antonio
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- With Houston's leading scorer sidelined with
an injury, Tiffani Johnson picked the right time to step up for the
Comets.

Johnson scored eight of her 10 points in overtime while filling
in for the injured Tina Thompson, and Houston beat the San Antonio
Silver Stars 69-66 for its third straight victory.

Thompson, who led Houston with 15 points, left the game at the
end of regulation with an injured left calf muscle. Sheryl Swoopes
added 14 points and 12 rebounds for the Comets.

"Anytime a great player like Tina Thompson gets hurt, it takes
two or three players to pick up the slack," Johnson said. "Before
the OT, I went up to Michelle Snow and said 'Let's be those
players, we have to pick it up in the OT.' Together we were very
aggressive in the overtime."

San Antonio, which lost its fifth straight game, was led by
Marie Ferdinand with 20 points. Semeka Randall added 12 points and
LaToya Thomas 10.

Trailing by as many as 14 points in the second half, San Antonio
ended regulation with a 19-6 run to send the game to overtime when
Thomas connected a short bank shot with 1.2 seconds remaining to
tie the score at 57.

"I thought when we were up 14 we took off a little bit," said
Houston coach Van Chancellor. "We really had to get tough on the
boards and rebound our way back into this one. Going into the
overtime without Tina Thompson, I thought we were in trouble.
That's were Tiffani Johnson was as big as she has ever been as a
member of the Houston Comets. If Tiffani doesn't play as well as
she does in overtime, we don't win."

Ferdinand scored consecutive baskets, her second a 3-pointer, as
San Antonio led 64-61 with 3:19 left in the extra session.

Snow led the Comets back with four straight points, her 15-foot
jump shot giving Houston a 65-64 lead with 1:39 to play.

Ferdinand responded with a driving layup, but Johnson's rebound
basket regained the lead for the Comets at 67-66 with 45.8 seconds
remaining.

San Antonio had three opportunities to regain the lead, but
Ferdinand, Thomas and Randall missed shots in the final 27 seconds.

"This was more of what we were looking for," San Antonio coach
Dee Brown said. "We gave ourselves a chance. Losses aren't good,
but we gave ourselves a chance and that's all you can ask for. We
fought back and as a coaching staff that's all you can ask your
players to do."

Johnson connected on two free throws with 4.5 seconds to play.
San Antonio couldn't get off a potential game-tying shot before the
final buzzer.
